##We stand with our Chinese counterparts, the Lancet, a group of eight experts, said in a joint statement

Micro Signal deeptechchina

Function description DeepTech is a full-chain content, service, data and investment and financing platform focusing on the emerging technology industrialization, and is committed to building a global network of scientific and technological innovation cooperation.

More and more details of the outbreak have emerged as the number of new crown pneumonia (COVID-19) cases has recently passed the 70,000 mark, China's Center for Disease Control and Prevention has issued the largest analysis of new crown cases to date and the first description of the epidemic curve of pneumonia.

At the same time, the rumors of human intervention of the new coronavirus, which had a strong mass base, are being refuted by scientific facts. The new coronavirus, for example, is "synthetic" .

Recently, several well-known scientists in the industry jointly published a preprint paper, detailed analysis of the new coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) in two suspected human intervention. In the end, the researchers concluded, the new coronavirus is not a manufactured virus that leaks out, but a product of the virus's natural evolution.

The article, entitled "The protoximal Origin of SARS-CoV-2" , is now known to have entered The submission stage. But the DEEPTECH E-MAIL team has yet to get any more replies.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Source: http://virological.org/） 

Co-authors of the article, also known as "stars are shining, " have been named by Discover magazine as "the world's most famous virus hunter, " and Columbia University professor W. Ian Lipkin, also an infectious disease geneticist from the prestigious Broad Institute. Andersen, Professor Andrew Rambaut, evolutionary biology, Edinburgh University.

As soon as the preprint was published, prominent virologists such as Columbia Professor Vincent Racaniello tweeted in support of the paper, praising it as providing a powerful counterattack to the human intervention of the new coronavirus.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Doubtful Point Analysis: viruses are not optimizations predicted by Algorithms, but more like natural selection

The new coronavirus is the seventh member of seven known coronavirus that can infect humans.

Among them, CoV-229E,-oc43,-nl63 and-HKU1 are prevalent in the population, usually causing common cold symptoms, the other three SARS-CoV, MERS-CoV, and this new coronavirus are serious harm, can lead to severe pneumonia and even death.

One of the major doubts that led to the synthesis of the novel coronavirus was its high affinity for the human ACE2 receptor. The ACE2 receptor is a key part of human-coronavirus binding, that is, the higher the affinity of the virus to human ACE2 receptor, the more transmissible the virus is.

Recently, the University of Texas at Austin published a study that analyzed the structure of the s protein of the new coronavirus in detail, as well as the affinity of the s protein to Ace2 using the Surface plasmon resonance technique.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fig. Mutation of the residue of SARS-CoV-2S protein (Source: http://virological.org/） 

The results showed that the s protein of the novel coronavirus was different from that of SARS virus in structure, but the similarity was high. And the ACE2 protein of the new coronavirus is 10 to 20 times more likely to bind to COVID-19 than the SARS virus, which is why the new coronavirus is more infectious.

Some of the key amino acid mutations that determine this trait are consistent with previous studies that have predicted amino acid mutations that can enhance affinity, so it is rumored that the virus was created by directed mutagenesis in the lab.

But the new paper suggests that the receptor binding domain (RBD) is the key part of the s protein binding to the ACE2 receptor of the new coronavirus, and the six amino acid residues in RBD determine the species range in which the coronavirus infects the host.

Five of the six residues (L455, F486, Q493, S494, N501 and Y505) of the new coronavirus were mutated compared with those of the rhinolophus coronaviruses with 96% similarity in gene sequence, this may explain the high affinity of npv to ACE receptors in humans, nonhuman primates, ferrets, pigs and cats, but not in humans. The presence of the amino acid F486 is more likely a natural evolutionary mutation of the new coronavirus against human and other animal hosts.

Moreover, the affinity of the new coronavirus to ACE2 is high, but its RBD is not the best choice. Scientists have previously analyzed the structure of the ACE2 receptor protein and predicted the amino acid sequence with the highest degree of matching, which is different from that found in the new coronavirus RBD. Several key amino acid residues in the new coronavirus RBD are completely different from those predicted by computational biology to be most suitable for binding to the human ACE2 receptor.

In short, as co-author Andrew Rambaut puts it: "The point is that the virus is perfectly suited to infect humans, but the way it infects humans is not the optimal answer currently given by the computational model. ". If evil biologists want to create such a deadly virus, this option is obviously not the best way.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fig. The full-length structure of ACE2, a receptor of the new coronavirus, has been successfully elucidated by using freeze electron microscopy in Zhou Qiang's lab. This is the first time in the world. ACE2 is the key to the entry of the new coronavirus into the body (Source: Westlake University) 

The team's other finding was that the new coronavirus had unusual polybase cutting sites that only existed after long, multigenerational transmission of avian influenza in cells or animals, moreover, the O-linked glycan structure can not be obtained by cell culture in the laboratory, and usually requires the involvement of the immune system.

Based on the genomic analysis of the novel coronavirus, "Importantly, this analysis provides evidence that the novel coronaviruses are neither produced in a laboratory nor manipulated virus, " the team wrote.

So where did the virus originate and how will it evolve?

The team gave two directions they thought they could focus on.

There's no time to lose

One possibility is that the new coronavirus has undergone natural selection and mutation in non-human animal hosts before being transmitted to humans.

Because of the outbreak of NCP in the south China Seafood Market in Wuhan, there may be a source of animal infection here. Moreover, the similarity of the neocoronavirus sequence to the SARS virus in bats (especially Rong13) is so great that bats are also well-documented as a source of the virus.

It should be noted, however, that previous human outbreaks of coronavirus have had animals other than bats in their transmission chain, such as SARS-CoV-1 and MERS-CoV. By analogy, a virus closely related to the new coronavirus may be circulating in one or more animals.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The new coronavirus is spreading around the world. The above model shows the most likely route for COVID-19 to travel from Beijing International Airport to airports around the world. The size of the bubbles represents the relative risk of each airport (Source: Dirk Brockmann

Preliminary analysis showed that coronaviruses had recently been found in illegally imported Sunda Pangolin, in which six important residues of the s protein RBD were consistent with SARS-CoV-2. But the entire Sunda Pangolin genome has not been identified to be sufficiently similar to the new coronavirus to support direct human infection. In addition, the Pangolin coronavirus also does not have the multi-base cutting site insertion. Therefore, the screening of coronavirus of suspicious animal origin will be the focus of tracing.

Another possibility is that the "ancestors" of the new coronavirus jumped directly from non-human animals to humans.

That would be even more frightening, because it would mean that the new coronavirus was gifted at evolving a high degree of "human fitness" : The asymptomatic ancestor of the new coronavirus quietly spread through the human population, until the mutation triggered an outbreak of pneumonia. So far, all new coronavirus genomes sequenced have significant RBD and multi-base cleavage sites, and the sequences of new coronavirus genes in different samples have high homology, which indicates that they have a common ancestor. These genomic characteristics are acquired by adaptation in the process of human-to-human transmission.

How do we test that the secret spread of the new coronavirus enhances its adaptability to humans? Retrospective serological studies may provide a reference, and we have seen some of these studies in progress.

In his tweet, Andrew Rambaut stressed that the neocoronavirus, which has no known bat virus function, may have originated in an earlier species of bat but then evolved in a different host. What is not clear is whether it evolved this high degree of "anthropomorphism" in non-human animals that are highly similar (at the cellular / Molecular Level) to humans.

Controlling the outbreak and finding other, more immediate intermediate hosts to prevent a recurrence will be top priorities, the article said.

Scientists launch a counterattack, the Lancet published a letter: Support Chinese public health professionals

Not long after Andrew Rambaut's team published the study, it was endorsed by many professionals, many of whom tweeted back that "the conspiracy theory is over. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fig. An earlier Indian paper calling the new coronavirus unnatural has been retracted (bioRxiv) 

After the COVID-19 incident in China, the spread of rumors and misinformation about the origin of the virus has frustrated scientists at home and abroad. These rumors are aimed specifically at scientists and health professionals, some of whom have made great efforts to fight the disease and share data in a rapid, open and transparent manner.

However, misinformation threatens to undermine the broad global cooperation that is essential to combat this new epidemic, which has spread across continents.

Now, a group of scientists around the world has called for science to counter the sinister rhetoric of the epidemic: A group of nearly 27 public health scientists from eight countries wrote letters in the Lancet in support of Chinese scientists, public health and medical professionals fighting the new pneumonia, and a full-scale attack on the sinister rhetoric.

Scientists include Sir Jeremy Farrar OBE, Jim Hughes (former assistant surgeon, former head of CDC NCID, United States Public Health Service) , rita Colwell (former head of the National Science Foundation) , Sai Kit Lam (professor of the National Academy of Medical Sciences and fellow of the Malaysian Academy of Medical Sciences, WHO co-discovered the Nipah Virus) , John Mackenzie (provost of Australia and member of the WHO GOARN Steering Committee) , dr. Jerry Keusch (former director of the NIH Fogarty International Center) and other leaders in Infectious Disease Research and public health.

The aim of the letter is to reach as wide an audience as possible at the critical moment of the new outbreak, to dispel unfounded rumours and to encourage and support their Chinese counterparts.
